{"branch":"claude/quizzical-rosalind","confidence":90,"prompt":"Test the March HTTP server from the REPL with CSV processing, math/string/enum operations on CSV content, and websocket support.

STEP 1: HTTP POST with CSV → parse → math/string/enum operations
STEP 2: WebSocket echo server test with wscat/websocat"}

{"branch":"claude/inspiring-mcnulty","confidence":95,"prompt":"Fix a REPL JIT bug where `let x = [1,2,3]` fails with `load ptr, ptr %march_compare_int.addr` — an invalid reference to a runtime function treated as a local variable.

ROOT CAUSE: In lib/tir/llvm_emit.ml, AVar handler falls through to .addr load pattern for runtime C functions like march_compare_int that are declared in preamble but not as allocas.

THE FIX: Add a check for march_ prefixed names before the .addr fallthrough in emit_atom's AVar handler."}

{"branch":"claude/eloquent-khayyam","confidence":90,"prompt":"Build the `forge` CLI tool for the March programming language. The full spec is at specs/plans/forge-spec.md — read it first.

Forge is an OCaml binary that lives in the March repo. Create it at `forge/` (separate from the compiler). It should have its own dune library/executable setup.

Implement these commands for v1: forge new, forge build, forge run, forge test, forge format, forge interactive / forge i, forge clean, forge deps."}

{"branch":"claude/magical-yonath","confidence":90,"prompt":"Implement two LSP code actions from specs/plans/lsp-code-actions-plan.md — Phase 1 items P1.1 and P1.7.

P1.1: Enhance fill-match-arms to generate typed stubs with field names derived from constructor signatures rather than _ -> todo!() stubs.

P1.7: Enhance add-type-annotation to handle function return type annotations (fn greet(name) -> String do) and function parameter annotations (fn greet(name: String) do), plus batch "annotate all unannotated bindings in file"."}

{"branch":"claude/beautiful-khayyam","confidence":95,"prompt":"Write a new spec at specs/plans/lsp-performance-insights-plan.md for a "Performance Insights" feature in the March LSP.

The core idea: the March compiler already knows a lot about what code will be fast or slow — tail call optimization, in-place memory reuse (FBIP/Perceus), atomic vs non-atomic reference counting, closure allocation, known vs indirect calls, escape analysis. The LSP should surface this knowledge as friendly, actionable diagnostics — like Elm's compiler errors, not Haskell academic jargon.

Commit with a descriptive message and update specs/todos.md and specs/progress.md."}

{"branch":"claude/angry-yonath","confidence":90,"prompt":"start working on specs/plans/elm-style-errors-plan.md

Read the plan file first to understand what needs to be done, then implement the Elm-style error message improvements it describes. The plan contains a full audit of every compiler diagnostic with before/after rewrites. Work through as many improvements as you can.

Key context: The user wants Elm-quality error messages — friendly, no compiler jargon, always suggest what to change. The error/warning messages live primarily in lib/typecheck/typecheck.ml, lib/errors/errors.ml, and related files."}

{"branch":"claude/optimistic-colden","confidence":95,"prompt":"You are a QA engineer. Your job is to adversarially test the Bastion web framework's stdlib modules by writing March test programs that exercise each feature, compiling them, and fixing any bugs you find.

Test areas: Request→Router→Response, Session middleware, Dev dashboard, CSRF protection, Caching, HTML templates, Islands module.

Write adversarial tests in examples/bastion_tests/, compile and fix bugs found, document in RESULTS.md."}

{"branch":"claude/recursing-dubinsky","confidence":90,"prompt":"Area 3 — Island conflict detection ❌ (not implemented, by design)
No mechanism exists at any layer. Islands are stateless WASM transforms (update(state_json, msg_json) → new_state_json). No version vectors, CRDTs, or OT. Concurrent island updates reduce to whichever of Vault.set/actor/Vault.update you use on the server — with the consistency properties above.

Build this out"}
